@dsoprea : It would get changed because in python assignment operator is essentially naming operator. 
```

>>> a = {'1': 2}
>>> b = a
>>> a['1'] = 3
>>> b
{'1': 3}
```

It's customary for cython modules to start with an underscore. I.e. Python implementation in fastdtw.py, Cython implementation in _fastdtw.pyx (and _fastdtw.so). You can then make the fast version preferred by adding at the bottom of fastdtw.py:
```py
def fastdtw(...):
    ... # python implementation

try:
    from ._fastdtw import fastdtw  # overrides above fastdtw
except ImportError:
    pass  # Compiled library not available. Perhaps issue a user warning.
```

Queued chunks as weird, and I think we want to avoid this setting.  My (admittedly poor) understanding of the Scala driver is that it has chunks of bytes queues and still serialized.  It then deserializes them on demand into messages and provides them to the user.  This seems odd to me because if you don't know the offset of the final message in a chunk (as it's still serialized), how do you know where to start fetching the next chunk?  It's all very confusing.

I talked with @yungchin about this a while back and IIRC librdkafka uses `max_messages_queued` which is simply the number of messages to keep in this per-partition queue.  It seems similar to how you've implemented `_queued_chunks`, so maybe all we need here is a name change.

@yungchin is my understanding of librdkafka here correct?  I remember us agreeing that the way there is better than the Scala driver

Because otherwise you can't do this:

