In this case I'd replace it with `console.error(error)`.  The thrown exception can't actually be caught, as the exception is thrown within an asynchronous block.   In other words, this wouldn't work.

```
try {
  runCorefModel(...)
} catch(err) {
  // You won't catch it here.
}
```

If you wanted the invoker to be able to handle the exception I'd simply return the result of `fetch` (so that the implementor can make a decision around control flow).  That said it doesn't seem like you need that flexibility here, so I'd just dump it to the console and call it good :).

